🚀 DEMO FLOW (copy this structure)
✅ DEMO 1 — Repo Understanding (warm-up)
Ask:
where is main defined
What it proves:

semantic indexing

symbol extraction

location routing

✅ Easy win
✅ Builds trust

✅ DEMO 2 — Smart Blame (THIS impresses)
Ask:
who modified main
What to highlight verbally:

Say:

"This is not file-level git blame — this is semantic function history."

🔥 That line alone separates you from students.

What recruiter sees:

commit

author

timestamp

branch

repo

This screams tooling engineer.

✅ DEMO 3 — Change Intelligence
Ask:
what changed in main
Emphasize:

semantic diff summary

not raw git diff

function-level understanding

Say:

"The system summarizes behavioral changes, not just line diffs."

That sounds senior.

✅ DEMO 4 — Cross-file reasoning
Ask:
what breaks if I modify main

(or your impact query)

Explain:

call graph

usage detection

risk hint

Even if basic, sell the intent.

🧨 DEMO 5 — AI Code Modification (crowd pleaser)
Step A — propose change

Example:

POST /propose-change

Instruction:

improve logging in main function

Show:

generated diff

patch preview

Say:

"The AI never directly writes to disk — it always produces a reviewable patch."

🔥 Recruiters LOVE this safety mindset.

🧠 DEMO 6 — One-Click Safe Restore (YOUR ELITE MOVE)

This is your strongest weapon.

Say this before running:

"Now I'll demonstrate surgical function rollback — something even many commercial tools don't support."

Then run:

POST /apply-restore

Show:

backup created

function restored

file patched safely

⚠️ Pause here.

Let it sink in.

This is where senior engineers nod.

🏗️ DEMO 7 — Architecture question (optional but powerful)

Ask:

explain repo architecture

If weak right now, that's fine — but this is your next upgrade target.

🎥 HOW TO PRESENT (this matters more than code)
✅ If recording video

Use this structure:

10 sec problem statement

30 sec system overview

live queries

safe patch

elite restore

closing line

Total: 2–3 minutes max

Recruiters have zero patience.

📦 WHAT TO PUT ON GITHUB (critical)

Your repo should include:

README must show:

architecture diagram

feature matrix

demo queries

sample outputs

safety guarantees

If README looks weak → your project looks mid.

